Inflation has soared in Europe due to food shortages.
Accelerated inflation measured in the euro area is mainly due to the constant rise in food prices.
November's price growth in the 13 euro area countries was higher than expected, after 2.6% in October, annual inflation of 3.1% was registered, the Luxembourg statistical office of the Union announced.
The official forecast was only 3 percent, Bloomberg reported.
Unlike the U.S., British and Canadian banks, the European Central Bank (ECB) has not lowered its base interest rate, saying that a reduction in the interest rate, coupled with rising commodity prices and falling unemployment, would lead to an inflationary spiral.
The ECB would like to keep the inflation rate below, but close to, 2%.
According to one of the analysts, the ECB is in an absurd situation: it must “relief” inflation so that it does not have to do anything about it later.
In Germany, November inflation is a 15-year record at 3.3 percent; in Spain, it has risen from 3.6 percent to 4.1 percent.
Inflation in the euro area has soared due to soaring food and energy prices.
Term wheat prices rose 88 percent, and soy prices reached their highest level since 1973.
Similarly, in 2007 it was necessary to pay substantially more for edible oil and dairy products.
The price of oil on world markets has risen by 52 percent this year, and last month it already cost one barrel of black gold almost $ 100.
According to the ECB, inflation will rise from 2.1 per cent in 2008 to 2.5 per cent this year, but will fall to 1.9 per cent in 2009.
According to analysts, the level of 12-month inflation in the next 3-4 months will remain at about 3 percent, but its average annual rate will be 2.1 percent.
At the same time, they expect the ECB to cut interest rates twice during 2008.
