In many places it is saved on disinfectants
This year, more than a thousand cases of infection were registered in hospitals, mainly due to inappropriate use of antibiotics.
The hygienic conditions of hospitals, the overcrowding of beds, the overcrowding of staff to stop diseases do not help, according to the head of the National Epidemiological Center.
In many places, it is also saved on disinfectants.
Recently, an MRSA infection was diagnosed in the trauma department of St. John’s Hospital.
Antibiotic-resistant bacteria have been discovered in a man who was rushed to hospital after a serious car accident.
The patient was isolated.
A similar infection occurred at the same site at the beginning of the year.
The patient injured in a serious car accident was released home, but not long after he had to return with MRSA infection and because of the bacteria in his body, one important operation could not be performed yet.
Until this December 10, 1,094 hospital-acquired infections caused by multidrug-resistant pathogens have been reported to the National System of Nesocomialis Surveillance, said Karolina B<0xC3><0xB6>r<0xC3><0xB6>czová, the head of the National Epidemiological Centre.
This means that so many infections caused by multidrug-resistant pathogens have been recorded in hospitals with certainty, the rest are not known.
Nearly two-thirds (683) of infections were caused by MRSA, or methicillin-oxacillin-resistant golden staphylococcus.
The bacteria Staphylococcus aureus (SA) is carried by a third of people in the nose without causing disease.
SA infections (e.g. cervical inflammation, tonsillitis, skin infections, early infections) respond well to antibiotics and can be well treated.
However, if antibiotics are given excessively or inappropriately, the antibiotic-responsive bacterium will develop into a bacterium that is very resistant to antibiotics and that spreads rapidly under inappropriate hospital conditions.
In particular, in the case of temporary or permanent malfunction of the immune system in patients with a weakened body, low body weight or in patients over the years, it can cause serious hospital infections, for example, an early infection or blood poisoning - sepsis.
According to the chief physician of St. John's Hospital, there is nothing special about MRSA infection, such an infection is a daily practice in hospitals.
"The infection must not be confused with the epidemic, MRSA is not only there," said Tibor Nyulasi, "where the presence of the causative agent of the disease is not investigated."
Resistant to antibiotics
"We isolate these patients, the nursing staff treats them in rubber gloves and in a mask, and we have the necessary antibiotics to treat them," said Tibor Nyulasi.
Patients admitted to the hospital are first examined for the presence of MRSA in their body, but even so, infection cannot always be avoided.
Sampling is not in fashion
The vast majority of hospital-acquired MRSA infections could be prevented, but the current conditions and conditions in home hospitals are not favorable for the prevention of the emergence and spread of multidrug-resistant pathogens, says Karolina B<0xC3><0xB6>r<0xC3><0xB6>czová.
Since this infection occurs characteristically in hospitals and nursing homes, hospitals receiving patients should check and isolate MRSA carriers immediately.
However, the collection of microbiological samples in Hungarian hospitals is not in vogue.
It is also important to note that the National Health Insurance Fund does not fund these tests.
Most cases are thus detected if the patient suffers from a perceptible MRSA infection, said the head of the epidemiology center.
The European Union has strict recommendations for the appropriate treatment with antibiotics in the field of human medicine, and there are also domestic guidelines for the treatment of individual infections, medical records.
Efforts should be made to ensure that antibiotic therapy is targeted, or microbiological testing should be carried out, in order to prevent the development of drug resistance, but even hospitals do not adhere to this in all cases.
Sampling of microbiological samples is even rarer in basic or outpatient treatment of patients, Karolina B<0xC3><0xB6>r<0xC3><0xB6>czová said.
Saves on disinfectants
According to scientific evidence, MRSA is most commonly spread among patients through medical personnel.
Therefore, hand washing and the use of gloves and masks play a very important role, but even in hospitals, serious deficiencies are manifested.
MRSA is transmitted by droplet infection and touch, but it is not always possible to isolate infected patients in home hospitals.
On the contrary, the rooms are often crowded, the beds are often very close to each other, although from an epidemiological point of view, patients should be at least 1.5 meters apart.
As Karolina B<0xC3><0xB6>r<0xC3><0xB6>czová noted, unfortunately, we can also encounter the fact that in hospitals that are in an unfavorable material situation, they are saving on disinfectants, there are few nurses and many patients, which increases the chances of developing infections even more.
According to Karolina B<0xC3><0xB6>r<0xC3><0xB6>czová, where the necessary protective measures are observed, there are demonstrably fewer such infections or the further spread of the causative agent of the disease can be stopped.
Government program against MRSA
Treatment of MRSA infection is a huge expense for health insurance companies, which is why it is fought everywhere.
For example, in England, the government has drawn up a program to prevent MRSA, or reduce its occurrence.
As it seems, the program is successful, according to published data, MRSA infections in England are showing a declining trend.
The European Centre for Disease Prevention and Control (ECDC) prioritises the prevention of multi-drug-resistant disease (MRSA) and hospital-acquired infections caused by these diseases.
