Fodor and Hungarian 6%
According to the Minister of Environment and Water Management Gábor Fodor, expert meetings will be closed on Tuesday, and after Wednesday's official opening, the international conference on the climate regime after 2012 will continue with the negotiations of the ministers.
Experts and politicians from 192 countries of the world are discussing the Bali Roadmap, which addresses the efforts following the period of emission reductions defined by the Kyoto Protocol in force until 2012.
At the moment, there is a tumultuous debate between developing and developed countries about them.
The United States has also announced that it does not now wish to negotiate exact figures, although it is committed to an agreement to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 25-40 percent by 2020 compared to 1990 levels.
The next big question of the conference is whether developed countries, in addition to reducing emissions, will also agree to provide both material and technological assistance to the countries that rely on it.
The agreement was also born on subsidies for developing countries.
The subsidy fund, set by the Kyoto Protocol, will be run by a 16-member governing council, most likely under the United Nations’ World Environment Programme (GEF) – we can read in the journal Piac és Profit.
Hungarian 6%
Environment and Water Minister Gábor Fodor, on behalf of Hungary, supports the EU's efforts to maintain its leading role in global climate protection efforts and to help create a new international agreement by 2009.
The minister said that the EU is committed to reducing greenhouse gas emissions by 20 percent by 2020 compared to 1990 levels, regardless of the success of the adoption of the "post-2012 agreement", and is ready to commit to up to 30 percent reduction if other developed regions of the world, respectively developed countries, are willing to accept responsibilities and commitments corresponding to their capabilities.
Gábor Fodor pointed out that the countries that joined the Kyoto Protocol in 1997 had set a reduction target of 5.2 per cent, with the then 15 EU Member States committing to 8 per cent.
The obligation of Hungary is to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 6 percent compared to the years 1985-87, which our country will fulfill.
In Bali, this is a big deal, because an international agreement on a long-term climate change policy needs to be adopted within two years, otherwise its entry into force would move with certainty only to 2012. In this case, the commitments to reduce the Kyoto Protocol would not be immediately followed by a new emission reduction system, the necessity of which in its latest report was also pointed out by the international scientific body of the UN, the IPCC dealing with climate change.
This would lead to a delay in reducing emissions and an inevitable increase in the average temperature of the Earth by more than 2 degrees Celsius, which, according to scientists, would have extremely serious and irreversible consequences.
The British army is recruiting on YouTube
British troops are posting videos of themselves popularizing events in Iraq and Afghanistan on a video-sharing server.
The British Air Force (RAF) first liked YouTube: special forces operating in Afghanistan have been uploading videos of anti-Taliban actions since March 2006, the BBC reported.
The recordings, taken with a miniature camera attached to the helmet, are controlled by the Air Force Command, which is in charge of combat operations in the Kandahar area, and then sent on to London, where they are transmitted to the Internet.
A Political Message is Inevitable
In this form, 139 recordings of soldiers of the British air force have already been made on the Internet, and more than 75,000 people have already looked at their "channel".
The British Ministry of Defence registered in the spring of 2007 as "defenseheadquarters" and publishes recordings of events in Iraq and Afghanistan, while the British Ministry of Foreign Affairs (Commonwealth Office) and the International Peace Forces in Iraq (MNFI) have their own YouTube channels.
Deployment in Afghanistan
The Air Force released the videos as originally intended for recruitment purposes, and according to the Department of Defense, they are also good for acquainting the general public with the real purpose of the army’s presence abroad.
"Promotions published in this form are almost worthless compared to traditional TV recruitment ads," defence expert Gordon Mackenzie told the BBC, "but they also necessarily carry a political message, as it confirms in a special form the legitimacy of military actions decided by the government."
The Americans made a game.
The army is concerned that, in addition to carefully edited, censored recordings, amateur videos are also uploaded to the server, capturing, for example, the death of soldiers: in a little hypocritical, "official" promotional films, officers mostly talk about losses, but the bloody form of the fight is not shown.
After all, many videos from the battlefields of Iraq and Afghanistan, which were created during a sharp deployment, have already been published on the Internet, but the British army has only just come to them now.
The Americans recruit a little differently - using a shooting game called America's Army, which is free to download and in which the player can get directly into the skin of soldiers through a more or less faithful simulation.
