Political Capital: Hungarian Guard Raises Country's Risk
The activity of the Hungarian Guard, founded with the support of the Jobbik Magyarországért movement in August this year, has increased the political risk of Hungary and the whole region in several respects, according to the Risk Analysing Division of the Political Capital Institute.
The "risk warning" developed by the company says: in connection with the activities of the Hungarian Guard, the greatest political risk is that "by aggravating the already existing ethnic tension between the Roma and non-Roma population of Hungary, violent ethnic clashes may occur in a short time."
The main reason is that the political strategy of the Hungarian Guard is probably aimed at provoking such an action, the research institute adds.
As he writes, all this can be explained by one of the greatest negligence of Hungarian political representatives: "public discussion on the Roma issue was left to the representatives of radical and extremist political groups, who could build a political strategy on the Roma-Hungarian contradiction."
This deepens the problem, prevents normal dialogue, strengthens extremists and increases the likelihood of violent conflict.
In addition, the activity of the Hungarian Guards, due to the great attention of domestic and foreign media, "largely damaged the image of Hungary abroad, especially in terms of faith in the stability of the country and its democratic development."
As part of the reorganisation of Hungary's radical and far-right groups, which have been gaining more and more publicity and vehemence since autumn 2006, the Institute recalls that several organisations have been formed in Hungary since the summer of 2007, calling themselves "national militias" associations.
