Holidays are not free everywhere
In Hungary, holidays are strictly defined by law and it has become common practice to move working days around the holidays, which is less likely to happen next year.
In the European Union and in America, the holidays are not uniform.
The Hungarian legal system distinguishes between national and state holidays and rest days.
Days of work rest are usually associated with church holidays or important historical events.
We also celebrate the New Year: the last day of the old and the first day of the new year is a work holiday - on New Year's Day, so that people can relax after New Year's Eve.
During the year we have a total of eleven free holidays.
The national holiday is March 15 celebrating the Revolution of 1848 and October 23, the memorial day of the Revolution of 1956.
On August 20, we celebrate the founding of the state, on May 1, work, and on November 1 and 2, we remember our deceased relatives and friends.
In addition, there are two-day holidays of Easter, Christmas and Christmas.
Since our national or religious holidays rarely fall on a weekend according to the calendar, it has become a practice to move the working day in cases where we would work only one day before or after a public holiday.
The price for extended weekends, however, is that the previous Saturdays we stayed at the workplace and at school.
When we work out the day immediately preceding or following the holiday, the Minister of Labour has been regulating it in a special decree for many years.
The legislation applies equally to all employers and their employees, to public employees and to persons in the public service.
However, it does not apply to companies and institutions that are in operation without interruption or with regard to their destination, they operate even on days of rest.
This year, there will be a change in the working schedule only around the holidays at the end of the year: from December 24, life in the country will almost stop, because, according to experience so far, most people will "work out" or use the saved vacation days between Christmas and New Year's Eve in advance.
Next year, several of our holidays fall in the middle, respectively, at the end of the week, so the shifts of the working day will be less than this year.
For the first time, the calendar is changed around Labor Day so that workers can then stay at home for four days of good taste.
Saturday, April 26, will be a working day, so that Friday, May 2, can be a day of rest.
The next move is related to the holiday of October 23: on Saturday, October 18, work will take place instead of Friday, October 24.
At the end of the year, however, next year will be able to take place entirely in the sign of the holidays, because from December 24 they will have non-stop holidays almost everywhere, despite the fact that New Year's Eve falls on Wednesday.
6 Disturbing Little Things You Can Do to Infuriate Your Colleagues
Emails we forget to send, voicemails we never receive, innocent lies we hardly notice anymore: they all “spend” the day in the workplace.
The question is whether you will get used to these minor inconveniences, or put on gloves, and avoid unclear situations that may make others angry.
Tips.
"I'm sorry, I forgot to tell you that they were looking for you from the marketing department," a colleague will tell you.
That you missed a meeting because of it?
At best, he regrets it and will try to fix it, or he will call the marketing department and say that he forgot to pass the message (this is a less common solution).
Most often, the matter is solved by one apology.
Before you make an embarrassing apology, it is good to think about how you can prepare your colleagues for unpleasant moments, and consciously try to avoid it.
Do you borrow something that is not yours?
There is nothing more unpleasant than when you reach for some document, office supplies or for your phone, and they are not there.
Remember you put a stapler on your desk last night, but it's gone by morning?
Or did you find a pen on the table of one of your colleagues that you thought was lost?
Do not take anything from your colleagues without permission, otherwise they will rightly be angry at you for going through their affairs.
Do not take away envelopes or sticky notes from the office, because it can be uncomfortable when you run out prematurely, and you will need them immediately.
Rumors about the private lives of colleagues?
There is no good solution to stop the spreading rumors.
Who, with whom, what did he do?
Where and why?
Don’t tell everyone about your colleagues’ private lives!
When one of them shares his innermost secret with you, don’t abuse his trust!
Lock in what you have heard, and in his absence, do not discuss it with your colleagues, even when others know about his things.
Are you reporting your absence for no reason?
If you call the office and report your absence with a severe headache because you are not feeling well, or you think that you would rather rest today, think about the fact that someone else will have to do your work, urgent tasks and work for which they have a certain deadline for you.
Take care of your colleagues!
If you know in advance that you will not go to work the next day, or that something may happen that will require you to stay at home, report it so that your colleagues and supervisors are not confronted with your absence until the next day.
Humping, giggles, phone calls
Have you immersed yourself in a work from which you are rudely snatched by the giggles of colleagues?
Have you accidentally witnessed a phone conversation that would be better not to hear at all?
Do not disturb your co-workers by humming, singing, talking loudly (over their heads), or stomping, cursing constantly, loud dissatisfaction.
All of this can be disruptive even when they are not involved in a project (writing, planning, organization).
Do you blame the mistakes of others?
If something is not on time or you have forgotten to send an important letter or message, do not blame the other person for your forgetfulness!
Do not appeal to any chaos in the office and noisy colleagues!
Admit if you made a mistake and someone paid for it, and fix the damage!
Ask how you could put things in order, correct the negligence!
Do you feel at home in the office?
Sweaters and slippers: comfortable clothes at home, but not suitable for the office!
Do not wear casual clothing, even if your profession allows it!
Do not be sloppy, honor your colleagues and yourself by coming to the office in a casual dress - and if your profession requires it, nicely and elegantly!
