The future of the province, where 90 percent of the Albanian-speaking population is expected to be clearer by December 10, when Ischinger, Wisner and Russian negotiator Alexander Bocan-Kharchenko are due to submit their report to the UN Security Council.
The talks in Baden, near Vienna, represent the sixth and final round of negotiations since the UN mandated the Troika to renegotiate in August this year.
Americans and Europeans are counting on the talks to end on December 10.
On the other hand, the Russians, who previously blocked Kosovo's independence in the UN Security Council, insist that negotiations continue beyond this latest deadline.
"Russia has been and remains in favor of a negotiated solution, a compromise solution," Bocan-Kharchenko said.
