Serbian President Boris Tadic, on the other hand, believes that a compromise is still possible and warned the Albanian majority in Kosovo against the consequences of the province's unilateral declaration of independence.
Belgrade is particularly concerned about the "dominant effect" in an area that is still unstable as a result of the wars of independence in the 1990s.
"But that does not mean for Serbia," he said, "that a compromise is impossible."
On Tuesday, the Serbian delegation insisted that all decisions should belong exclusively to the Security Council, in which its Russian ally has the right of veto.
