The 47 million archive documents stored in Bad Arolsen (Hesse) for 27 km have so far been accessible only for "humanitarian" purposes, i.e. individually and specifically, at the request of the former victim or his/her beneficiaries.
Eleven states tasked with managing the archives — including Germany, France, Israel and the United States — agreed in May to open them to scientists and historians.
As the process of ratification of this agreement by all states is over, the opening took effect yesterday.
