Congress Approves MiFID Transposition Effective November 1
In parallel with the parliamentary negotiations that were concluded today by a congressional vote on the Senate amendments to the bill, the government has submitted to a public hearing a regulation that develops the new law, with the aim of both coming into force before the end of the year.
The representatives of the parties unanimously highlighted the efforts of Members and Senators to negotiate and agree on the best standard to guarantee investor protection and detailed regulation of the activities of the entities necessary for the effective functioning of the markets.
The MiFID Directive, which regulates the Securities Trading Act, provides for the modernisation of financial markets while strengthening investor protection, improving the supervisory powers of the State Securities Market Commission (CNMV) and promoting cooperation between the various supervisory authorities of the European Union.
This new regulation will allow financial advisory services to be provided to both specialised firms and natural or legal persons, and creates a new type of financial advisory firm (ESIS), financial advisory firm (AFI) that joins securities firms, securities brokerage firms and portfolio management companies.
In addition, the number of systems for executing transactions in financial instruments is expanding by connecting multilateral trading systems and order internalisation systems to regulated secondary markets, which will compete with current stockbrokers.
The Act also obliges investment services companies to disseminate information on key aspects of their business profile, exposure to risk and ways of dealing with risk on the market and requires a statement of all operations performed to facilitate supervision by the CNMV.
During its deliberations in the Congressional Trade Commission, several adjustments were included, among which the one that stands out is that securitized receivables are considered a “complex” financial instrument due to the high risk to the investor that has been demonstrated by what has happened in the U.S. with high-risk subprime mortgages.
Moreover, the transposition of the directive has been used to legally define the functions that bachelors in economics and business management can hold 30 years after the Royal Decree was adopted in 1977, which sets out the professional functions reserved for economists.
At the same time, the Senate included the creation of new professions in the financial sector, such as an intermediary that will work externally, will not require permission from CNMV and will be able to provide product trading services and client acquisition for various investment firms at the same time.
