Concerns over new gas dispute between Russia and Ukraine
A gas price dispute is currently underway between Russia and Ukraine, increasing the risk that Russian supplies of this fuel to Western Europe may be affected.
Most of the Russian fuel exported to the European Union (EU) is piped through Ukraine, and any dispute between the two countries is being closely watched.
Kiev has warned that if Moscow raises gas prices for Ukraine, it will charge Russia higher transit fees.
A previous dispute between the two last year reduced supplies to EU countries.
The latest dispute between Kiev and Moscow comes as the Ukrainian government and Russia’s state-owned gas monopoly, Gazprom, are trying to agree on how much Ukraine will have to pay for Russian gas in 2008.
Gazprom says it will have to charge Ukraine more because it agreed to pay up to 50% more for gas it gets from neighboring Turkmenistan.
Analysts say this could mean Ukraine will have to pay 40% more for its supplies from Gazprom.
“It is important for us to use our arguments as one of the most important gas transit states during the negotiations,” Ukrainian Economy Minister Anatoly Kinakh told Reuters.
“Changes in gas prices should no doubt be linked to our arguments regarding the amount of transit fees (to Western Europe) through Ukraine.”
The latest major dispute between Moscow and Kiev caused a cut in supplies from Gazprom to Ukraine in January 2006.
This caused a crushing drop in exports to Western Europe, which sharply increased prices.
Russian gas accounts for a quarter of EU supplies.
Russia has the largest gas reserves in the world, but much of it remains underutilized.
As a result, Gazprom is supplementing its own gas supplies with gas from Turkmenistan and other former Soviet Central Asian republics.
NHS 'must check foreign workers'
The Comptroller said the Scottish NHS Chambers must improve criminal records checks on non-European staff.
The recommendation from the president of the Supreme Audit Office, Robert Black, came after a foreign doctor operating in Scotland was linked to the June attacks on Glasgow Airport.
Mr Black is also concerned that the Scottish NHS does not have an accurate picture of the amount of foreign staff it employs.
But his report highlighted that other key checks had been carried out in order on a sample of five health authorities.
The President of the Supreme Audit Office was interested in personnel from countries outside the European Economic Area immediately after the June attacks on Glasgow Airport.
Twenty-eight-year-old Bilal Abdullah, an Iraqi doctor at the Royal Alexandra Hospital in Paisley, was detained at the airport after someone drove a Jeep into the door of the main terminal building.
He was one of three doctors who appeared at the Central Criminal Court using a video bridge accused of being linked to the bombings in the UK.
The NHS Chambers are expected to check foreign staff in terms of qualifications, experience and authorisation to work in the UK prior to their employment.
Although Scottish Health Commissions use Disclosure Scotland to monitor criminal records, the agency has no authority to obtain such information outside the UK.
The report by the President of the Supreme Audit Office says, among other recommendations, that commissions should be guided by the Criminal Records Bureau guidelines, which helps employers with inspections in several countries.
"Although we found that some of the personnel records contained evidence of these checks, they are not conducted regularly," the report said.
Mr Black said the Scottish NHS was largely in line with its own pre-employment screening policy, but added: “Our report highlights areas where the system could be improved to ensure the availability of accurate information on the number of foreign staff.”
BMA Scotland chairman Dr Peter Terry said it was “very unlikely” that pre-employment checks would identify potential NHS staff who could commit a terrorist act in the future.
"The report suggests that the current pre-employment checks in the Scottish NHS are working well and it is not clear what further value the comments will bring," he said.
Scottish health authorities say they currently have 1,161 foreign workers, the vast majority of whom are doctors and nurses.
However, the president of the Supreme Audit Office pointed out that these numbers will probably be higher also because the commissions had trouble identifying the staff with a residence permit.
The survey also found that the established control procedures at NHS bodies in the Ayrshire and Arran, Grampian, Greater Glasgow and Clyde, Lanarkshire and Lothian areas are largely being implemented.
They included checks on passports, work permits and qualifications.
