Scientists have announced that Venus may have once been a pleasant place to live.
Data from an orbiting European station shows that the planet is even more like Earth’s headstrong twin than previously thought.
Venus is Earth’s closest planetary neighbor.
These two worlds are roughly the same size and orbit similar orbits, but Venus is a little closer to the Sun.
Scientists now believe that billions of years ago conditions on Venus were similar to those on Earth and could have been habitable.
But the scorched greenhouse effect caused by carbon dioxide, atmospheric erosion by solar radiation, and lower rotational speeds sent Venus on a completely different path of development.
Today, the planet is without water, the surface temperature is hot enough to melt lead, and it is ravaged by storms and hurricane-force winds.
Findings from the European Space Agency's Venus Express probe, which has studied the planet for a year, offer a sobering look at how the Earth could evolve in the event of catastrophic climate change.
Professor Fred Taylor, from the University of Oxford’s Department of Physics and one of the Venus Express mission leaders, said: “It is becoming increasingly clear why the climate on Venus is so different from that on Earth, even though the planets themselves are otherwise quite similar.
