The Pain of Labour
Gordon Brown once again found a trap he could fall into; his way out remains the same.
Although this is common in British political scandals, it is not particularly spicy.
It does not seem that any orders were sold, no bills in the Paris hotel were mysteriously paid, no extramarital fingers were sucked.
But a barricaded Gordon Brown would do without discovering that some wealthy businessman had been masking the <0xC2><0xA3>650,000 (US$1.3 million) contributions to the ruling Labour Party for four years under other people’s names, and that the party had not announced it.
Two months ago, when the prime minister avoided calling an election and insulted British intelligence by claiming that the decision had not been influenced by polls, there was hope that it would ensure a resilient and effective government.
Instead, as the increasingly humorous Liberal Democrat deputy chairman put it, the once-feared Mr. Brown changed from Stalin to Mr. Bean.
The clumsy rescue of troubled Northern Rock Bank showed weaknesses in management and weak judgment under fire.
The ill-conceived proposals to change the tax code have brought companies together against the government.
The loss of personal data in 25 million people has revealed an unimaginable administrative blunder.
The three retired generals launched a mutiny in the House of Lords; they protested against cuts in military spending, claiming that being commander of the armed forces was part-time work.
Now there are multiple gifts from David Abrahams; Peter Watt, Labour’s secretary-general (and their former guardian of internal discipline), has resigned.
None of this means that Mr. Brown is irrevocably heading for his end.
Despite this, governments can reach a tipping point beyond which they find governance difficult.
People don’t trust politicians and don’t like them, but they usually put aside their mistrust when a new gang takes over.
When it seems clear that a prime minister is unlikely to improve anything, and may not even be in office for long, this shift is over: the state administration is becoming leaky, ministers are starting to brief, the press is looking for bad news, and the government is becoming unfocused and defensive.
In one way, Mr Brown's position is particularly difficult because he cannot take the position of a new broom compared to other political leaders.
As much as he wanted to distance himself from Tony Blair, he was his first officer.
For example, the problems with Northern Rock and the records of the tax office are linked to the decisions Mr. Brown made as finance minister.
And while he wasn’t directly involved in Blair’s troubles, such as a lengthy investigation into the funding of political parties caused by “values for money,” voters can safely conclude that he was.
Still, Mr. Brown's difficulties are not as bad as they seem.
They’re not as bad as conservatives make them out to be.
As far as Mr Bean is concerned, no one has died or been outright deceived.
And the cure, however painful it may be, is to provide what Mr. Brown’s Stalinist tendencies have always promised: reliable, solid, and lightly brutal government.
The latest uproar over political gifts is a good example.
Garboid Mr. Abrahams, who compares his gifts to charity, says he didn’t want any publicity for his charity.
That may be true, but the decision was not his.
Laws against the anonymity of major political donors are clear and exist for a simple reason: the public has a right to know who could buy access to those who rule the country.
Mr. Watt, who said he knew of Mr. Abrahams's conduct but did not know it was illegal, will certainly be thoroughly interrogated; so will Jon Mendlesohn, the chief Labour money-seeker who learned of the fraudulent gifts in October.
But so far Mr. Brown has been uninvolved; there is nothing to suggest that he knew of these intrigues, though the bulk of the payments were made after his arrival in June.
So far, the Prime Minister has done half the work.
He very quickly condemned this violation of the laws on his own part, but diluted his resolve by reaching for a proven instrument, a commission of inquiry on the matter - led in addition by a retired bishop and a judge.
In this case, the lessons are not complex.
If the law has been broken, it is a matter for the police.
In addition, there are other things that Mr Brown has to do, such as finding the permanent chairman of the independent Committee on Standards in Public Life, which has not had one for six months, and moving forward with a real reform of the financing of political parties.
That would require Labour, who are in a tight spot, to co-operate with the Conservatives and perhaps even give up their special financial relationship with the unions - bitter pills for a dedicated party member like Mr Brown.
But he should face some simple facts.
Conservatives now have a decent lead in polls; he has two years to win back voters; and the only way to win is with unassailable integrity and high competence.
