Does the subprime mortgage crisis affect the U.S. credit card market?
When there is blood in the water, the dorsal fins naturally begin to quiver excitedly.
Now that the U.S. real estate market is in decline, the predators have focused on the credit card market there.
Goldman Sachs analysts say credit card losses from subprime mortgages could reach $99 billion.
The signs of tension are clear.
The number of cases of inability to repay (in case of more than 30-day delay in payment) and accounts written off (accounts that the provider considers unenforceable) is increasing.
HSBC said last month it had lost $1.4 billion in the U.S. consumer credit market — also due to insolvent credit card loans.
However, it is still too early to panic.
Depreciated accounts and inability to repay are still few.
According to Moody’s, the third quarter’s default rate of 3.89% was almost a full percentage point below the average.
Deteriorating rates can be partly explained by technical reasons.
The change in the U.S. Personal Bankruptcy Act of 2005 led to a sharp decline in the number of reported bankruptcies that make up a large portion of credit card losses; the number of reports (and thus the number of write-offs) would therefore rise regardless of whether the general conditions for borrowers worsened.
The industry also shows a good level of maturity, which shows how much consumers pay back from their debts per month.
And trust in the securities of secured credit cards is solid, despite the paralysis in other corners of structured finance.
Mr. Dennis Moroney of the TowerGroup research firm predicts that their emissions for 2007 will be 25% higher than last year.
There are certainly direct ways to spread the infection between the subprime mortgage crisis and the credit card market: when property loans dry up, consumers are more likely to be indebted via credit cards.
Credit card issuers, however, tend to look at cash flow rather than the value of guaranteed items, so falling house prices do not necessarily mean a change in the credibility of borrowers.
They can even be beneficial to lenders.
Consumers’ motivation to repay their mortgages falls when the value of their assets falls below the value of the loan; as a result, card debt moves up the list of priorities for repayment.
Card issuers are also able to respond more quickly and flexibly to more turbulent conditions than mortgage providers by changing interest rates or debt limits.
This should, in theory, reduce the risks of a rapid change in the prices of guarantee items.
“It’s not going to happen that one fine morning we just reassess all the loans,” said Gary Perlin, chief financial officer at Capital One.
While the risk of a subprime-style explosion is low, the risk of a gradual weakening is far more real.
If lower home prices and debt reduction push America into recession, the credit card industry will face a darker future.
Watch out for those dorsal fins.
