Venus is Earth’s twin infernal.
Venus Express, the European spacecraft on Venus, has recorded phenomena that also occur on Earth in winter: lightning in the atmosphere and winds whirl at the poles.
For nearly three decades, scientists have suspected that Venus is glowing.
Now the European probe Venus Express has brought evidence - captured electromagnetic waves at the edge of the atmosphere. On Venus, lightning flies from cloud to cloud at an altitude of about 56 kilometers, wrote in the scientific journal Nature Christopher Russell from the University of California, Los Angeles.
According to a well-known theory of the formation of primordial matter, lightning was able to give rise to life on Earth. Storms allegedly triggered reactions in the oceans that led to the formation of amino acids, the cornerstones of life.
“If life ever existed there, it must have been a long time ago,” explains Sean Solomon of the Carnegie Institution of Washington.
The atmosphere is about a hundred times denser than that of Earth, and sometimes temperatures are around 500 °C.
"Venus may be Earth's infernal twin, but he's a twin," Russell said.
Why Venus, which is so similar to Earth in mass and size, began to evolve in a completely different way is a fundamental question of the ESA mission.
Since no spacecraft has been sent to study Venus since the early 1990s, the launch of Venus Express in November 2005 was a milestone in the exploration of the planet.
According to scientists, the latest results of the research, which brought closer several articles of the journal Nature, not only emphasized the uniqueness of Venus in the solar system.
"They also showed that our neighboring planet is more Earth-like than previously thought," Esa said.
In addition to the already known wind vortices at the North Pole, scientists have found a cloud vortex at the South Pole that rotates much faster.
This phenomenon resembles air currents in the Earth's northern hemisphere, writes a research team led by Guiseppe Piccioni of the Italian Institute of Astrophysics Spaziale e Fisica Cosmica.
The second innermost planet of our solar system is almost the same mass as Earth, and with a diameter of 12,100 km, it is almost the same size.
This planet, known as Jit<0xC5><0x99>enka or Ve<0xC4><0x8D>ernice, will orbit the Sun in about 225 days.
However, it rotates much more slowly around its own axis. One day on Venus lasts 243 days on Earth.
Although Venus has a surface temperature of 460 °C and a pressure of 92 bar, scientists assume that the two planets were formed under very similar conditions.
Water accumulated on both of them, but it remained in the oceans on Earth, while it evaporated into space from Venus.
While carbon dioxide on Earth is bound in carbonates on Earth, it makes up most of the atmosphere on Venus.
