These aren't Warhol's boxes.
Anyone who combines the terms Sweden and wooden boxes is not thinking of Andy Warhol, but of Ikea.
Or is it?
Wooden boxes currently produced in Sweden cast dark shadows on the list of Warhol’s works.
Most of his list of ninety-four "Brillo boxes" of the Stockholm type are counterfeits.
After the Swedish newspaper "Expressen" a few months ago expressed doubts about the authenticity of the Warhol's "Brillo boxes" of 1968, comes the internal research of the Museum of Moderna Museet in Stockholm with the result that brought disappointment; six "Brillo boxes" that in 1995 the Museum of Moderna Museet's director had given a gift to him.
Previous events are a tangled, confusing chain of artistic and curatorial events.
Warhol made his first Brillo boxes in New York City in 1964, painting wooden boxes that were based on the red-and-blue design of Brillo soap powder paper boxes.
The exhibition of his works in the Moderna Museet in 1968 showed - with Warhol's consent - hundreds of Brillo boxes made of cardboard. These did not come (for financial reasons) from Warhol, but were delivered directly from the Brillo factory.
These were not works of art, but their designs, mere exhibition pieces.
Warhol apparently also gave permission in 1968 for several wooden Brillo boxes to be made in Sweden, but they are not on display at the Moderna Museet.
The witnesses of the time now speak of fifteen boxes, which at that time rightly entered the art and auction history as authorized originals - "Andy Warhol's Brillo Boxes" with the designation Typ Stockholm.
Some of them were auctioned for more than $100,000.
The problem now is that the museum’s legendary director, Pontus Hultén, later falsely claimed that approximately one hundred boxes had been produced and exhibited in Sweden in 1968, which Warhol then left to him.
In fact, 105 Hultén boxes were made in Malm<0xC3><0xB6> for the St. Petersburg exhibition only in 1990.
By that time, Warhol was already three years dead.
Lars Bystr<0xC3><0xB6>m, Chief Conservator of Moderna Museet, examined, in addition to the six Brillo boxes that are owned by the museum, three Brillo boxes from the Swedish private collection, two of which were made in Sweden in 1968 and after their plywood boards were painted with base paint and sanded.
From the structure of the copies from 1990, on the contrary, it turned out that the paint was applied directly to the plywood plate without any previous primer paint - besides, it is an acrylic and not an oil paint.
"These boxes were not authorized by the artist and should be removed from Warhol's official list of Brillo boxes," Moderna Museet's director, Lars Nittve, said: "If Andy Warhol's Art Authentication Board in New York does not come to any other conclusions, Moderna Museet will have to copy six boxes from its exhibition collections as a collection of classics."
As early as July, the Authentication Board announced that it would look into these “core allegations” raised in the case of soap powder boxes.
But the organization is still in inexorable silence.
